Timestamping means automatically storing date and time information for database records.

Common fields:

created_date → when record is created

updated_date → when record is modified

This feature is supported in Spring Data JPA.

1️⃣ Enable JPA Auditing

Add annotation in the main class.

@SpringBootApplication
@EnableJpaAuditing
public class Application {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args);
    }

}

@EnableJpaAuditing enables automatic timestamp tracking.

2️⃣ Entity Class with Timestamp
import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import jakarta.persistence.*;
import org.springframework.data.annotation.CreatedDate;
import org.springframework.data.annotation.LastModifiedDate;
import org.springframework.data.jpa.domain.support.AuditingEntityListener;

@Entity
@EntityListeners(AuditingEntityListener.class)
public class Employee {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Integer empId;

    private String empName;

    @CreatedDate
    private LocalDateTime createdDate;

    @LastModifiedDate
    private LocalDateTime updatedDate;

}
3️⃣ What Happens

When a new record is inserted:

createdDate  → automatically filled
updatedDate  → automatically filled

When record is updated:

updatedDate → automatically updated
Example Table
emp_id	emp_name	created_date	updated_date
1	Rishav	2026-03-13 10:10	2026-03-13 10:10

After update:

emp_id	emp_name	created_date	updated_date
1	Rishav	2026-03-13 10:10	2026-03-13 11:30
Common Timestamp Annotations
Annotation	Purpose
@CreatedDate	stores creation time
@LastModifiedDate	stores last update time
